1
00:00:00,348 --> 00:00:05,684
AI DevKit is an operating model for AI-centric software engineering.

2
00:00:06,429 --> 00:00:10,518
AI writes specs, tests, code, and docs.

3
00:00:11,356 --> 00:00:14,159
Humans approve the spec and approve the release.

4
00:00:15,423 --> 00:00:18,518
It works with your existing stack — git,

5
00:00:18,606 --> 00:00:23,931
repos, pull requests, continuous integration — and reshapes it around

6
00:00:24,091 --> 00:00:28,484
AI execution, while keeping the human checkpoints that matter.

7
00:00:29,992 --> 00:00:32,960
There are four pillars: spec planning,

8
00:00:33,055 --> 00:00:38,088
test-driven implementation, Progressive Disclosure docs, and the AI

9
00:00:38,189 --> 00:00:39,368
dev environment.

10
00:00:39,706 --> 00:00:41,765
Work comes in as a story,

11
00:00:41,862 --> 00:00:44,006
epic, bug, or feature.

12
00:00:45,031 --> 00:00:48,320
It flows through three phases: Plan,

13
00:00:48,368 --> 00:00:50,081
Implementation, and Release.

14
00:00:51,659 --> 00:00:54,322
The Lead AI executes the workflow.

15
00:00:55,585 --> 00:00:56,878
The Verify A.I.

16
00:00:56,951 --> 00:01:02,311
independently reviews all Lead AI work — it's a second AI

17
00:01:02,376 --> 00:01:04,709
from a different training lineage.

18
00:01:04,932 --> 00:01:05,990
Why two AIs?

19
00:01:07,365 --> 00:01:12,472
A single AI is confidently wrong in ways invisible to itself.

20
00:01:13,429 --> 00:01:17,671
Asking the same model to review its own output rarely catches the

21
00:01:17,724 --> 00:01:18,069
error.

22
00:01:19,632 --> 00:01:22,867
Two independent lineages catch different mistakes.

23
00:01:24,447 --> 00:01:26,865
The Plan phase produces a spec.

24
00:01:27,834 --> 00:01:30,625
The Implementation phase produces working code,

25
00:01:30,717 --> 00:01:33,342
tests, and updated docs.

26
00:01:34,174 --> 00:01:39,337
That deliverable passes through Release — continuous integration and delivery

27
00:01:39,418 --> 00:01:42,299
pipelines plus human approval.

28
00:01:42,567 --> 00:01:45,656
Plan turns a work item into an approved spec.

29
00:01:47,377 --> 00:01:49,413
The Lead AI reads the requirement,

30
00:01:49,433 --> 00:01:54,618
the docs, and the code, then drafts a spec with acceptance criteria,

31
00:01:54,666 --> 00:01:57,893
edge cases, and approach decisions.

32
00:01:58,832 --> 00:01:59,969
The Verify A.I.

33
00:02:00,070 --> 00:02:02,128
reviews the spec independently.

34
00:02:03,383 --> 00:02:07,487
If the two AIs disagree on what a criterion means,

35
00:02:07,691 --> 00:02:12,528
that's ambiguity — and it gets surfaced to the human before any

36
00:02:12,593 --> 00:02:13,487
code is written.

37
00:02:15,316 --> 00:02:18,921
The key discipline here: decide in the spec,

38
00:02:19,021 --> 00:02:20,201
not in the code.

39
00:02:21,688 --> 00:02:25,169
If you let the AI defer decisions to implementation,

40
00:02:25,314 --> 00:02:29,164
it makes them implicitly, often inconsistently,

41
00:02:29,295 --> 00:02:31,881
and you only find out when you're reading the code.

42
00:02:33,540 --> 00:02:36,043
The phase ends when the human signs off.

43
00:02:36,824 --> 00:02:40,205
Implementation turns the approved spec into working code.

44
00:02:42,104 --> 00:02:43,245
The Verify A.I.

45
00:02:43,314 --> 00:02:46,526
authors the failing tests directly from the spec.

46
00:02:48,269 --> 00:02:52,807
The Lead AI writes the implementation to make them pass.

47
00:02:53,795 --> 00:02:58,204
This is independent test authorship — the AI that writes the tests

48
00:02:58,311 --> 00:03:01,763
is not the AI that writes the code.

49
00:03:02,908 --> 00:03:08,430
Without that separation, implementation assumptions get silently baked into the tests.

50
00:03:10,340 --> 00:03:15,473
After TDD completes, the Lead AI updates the Progressive Disclosure docs,

51
00:03:16,176 --> 00:03:17,388
and the Verify A.I.

52
00:03:17,444 --> 00:03:20,187
checks the updates against the actual code.

53
00:03:21,826 --> 00:03:23,588
Then the spec is archived.

54
00:03:24,012 --> 00:03:26,027
The docs carry everything forward.

55
00:03:26,419 --> 00:03:29,945
Progressive Disclosure docs give every repo the same structure.

56
00:03:30,732 --> 00:03:33,792
The same eight files, in every repo,

57
00:03:33,838 --> 00:03:35,640
across the whole organisation.

58
00:03:36,877 --> 00:03:41,084
Level zero is an identity card — what is this repo?

59
00:03:42,253 --> 00:03:45,568
Level one is eight fixed files:

60
00:03:45,967 --> 00:03:51,171
setup, architecture, code map, conventions, workflows,

61
00:03:51,251 --> 00:03:54,371
interfaces, gotchas, and security.

62
00:03:55,824 --> 00:04:00,771
Level two is deep dives, loaded only when Level one isn't enough.

63
00:04:01,902 --> 00:04:05,847
Levels zero and one load upfront — they're small.

64
00:04:06,496 --> 00:04:09,256
Level two is pulled in only when needed.

65
00:04:09,959 --> 00:04:13,893
The agent gets full context without filling the context window.

66
00:04:15,151 --> 00:04:19,413
That consistency is what lets any agent pick up any repo and

67
00:04:19,492 --> 00:04:20,453
work safely.

68
00:04:20,655 --> 00:04:24,056
Real systems span multiple repos — an API,

69
00:04:24,083 --> 00:04:27,173
an SDK, a frontend, shared infrastructure.

70
00:04:28,592 --> 00:04:32,612
The AI dev environment gives you one workspace where the AI can

71
00:04:32,672 --> 00:04:34,935
run the whole system end to end.

72
00:04:35,876 --> 00:04:38,373
It's a container of containers.

73
00:04:39,063 --> 00:04:41,656
Each component runs in its own container,

74
00:04:41,788 --> 00:04:44,052
all inside one outer workspace.

75
00:04:45,391 --> 00:04:47,729
The Lead AI can start, stop,

76
00:04:47,809 --> 00:04:50,771
restart, and test any component from there.

77
00:04:51,872 --> 00:04:53,890
It runs locally or in the cloud.

78
00:04:55,261 --> 00:05:00,119
Cloud workspaces are useful for team handoff — another engineer picks up

79
00:05:00,159 --> 00:05:03,519
the same workspace and the same context.

80
00:05:04,338 --> 00:05:10,197
The environment includes Playwright for browser testing and Terraform for infrastructure.

81
00:05:10,816 --> 00:05:16,204
And there's an audit trail across all agent sessions — reproducibility,

82
00:05:16,257 --> 00:05:20,525
traceability, and evals for debugging agent behaviour.

83
00:05:20,982 --> 00:05:25,401
Everything in AI DevKit runs through six markdown files in a prompts

84
00:05:25,470 --> 00:05:25,964
folder.

85
00:05:27,406 --> 00:05:32,523
spec, implement, create docs, update docs,

86
00:05:32,603 --> 00:05:35,966
verify with Codex, verify with Claude.

87
00:05:37,543 --> 00:05:40,362
They're plain text — you can read them,

88
00:05:40,413 --> 00:05:43,962
understand exactly what the AI is being told to do,

89
00:05:44,022 --> 00:05:45,162
and modify them.

90
00:05:46,829 --> 00:05:49,645
Why not skills or slash commands?

91
00:05:51,226 --> 00:05:54,847
There are lots of ways to load instructions into an AI tool

92
00:05:55,207 --> 00:05:59,723
— user settings, project files, enterprise configs,

93
00:05:59,826 --> 00:06:02,206
skills, slash commands.

94
00:06:02,751 --> 00:06:04,125
It's a walled garden.

95
00:06:05,660 --> 00:06:07,885
A Claude skill doesn't work in Cursor.

96
00:06:09,260 --> 00:06:11,807
A Cursor command doesn't work in Codex.

97
00:06:13,306 --> 00:06:14,367
But at the end of the day,

98
00:06:14,420 --> 00:06:17,247
it's all just text hitting an LLM.

99
00:06:18,271 --> 00:06:22,283
Prompts are portable — you can paste them into any agent,

100
00:06:22,336 --> 00:06:24,282
or pipe them from the command line.

101
00:06:25,816 --> 00:06:30,514
Curl the prompts straight from GitHub — no clone needed.

102
00:06:31,293 --> 00:06:36,277
For example: curl create-docs and verify-codex,

103
00:06:36,437 --> 00:06:37,957
pipe to claude.

104
00:06:39,302 --> 00:06:44,193
Or flip it — curl create-docs and verify-claude,

105
00:06:44,321 --> 00:06:45,792
pass to codex.

106
00:06:47,379 --> 00:06:52,823
Either way, one command generates Progressive Disclosure docs and runs

107
00:06:52,890 --> 00:06:56,591
cross-model verification — end to end,

108
00:06:56,698 --> 00:07:00,683
about fifty minutes, zero human intervention.

109
00:07:02,871 --> 00:07:05,127
Visible prompts are accountable.

110
00:07:05,213 --> 00:07:08,363
Hidden skills may or may not be followed.

111
00:07:09,555 --> 00:07:14,689
Engineers should read the prompts, not trust hidden instructions.

112
00:07:14,824 --> 00:07:15,727
Here's how to start.

113
00:07:17,605 --> 00:07:18,530
Pick one repo.

114
00:07:20,624 --> 00:07:26,364
Curl create-docs, pipe to claude — or pass to codex.

115
00:07:27,374 --> 00:07:31,242
That's it — any agent can then pick up that repo and

116
00:07:31,307 --> 00:07:32,126
work safely.

117
00:07:34,036 --> 00:07:39,084
Chain verify-codex or verify-claude for cross-model review — works

118
00:07:39,137 --> 00:07:40,845
in either direction.

119
00:07:41,915 --> 00:07:52,210
The repo, the standard, and all the prompts are open at github.com/AgoraIO-Community/ai-devkit.

